Here are both approaches in .NET MAUI Shell navigation:

**1. Register the route**
```csharp
// AppShell.xaml.cs
Routing.RegisterRoute("productdetails", typeof(ProductDetailsPage));
```

**2. Navigate — string ID vs full object**
```csharp
// ProductListViewModel.cs
[RelayCommand]
async Task SelectProduct(Product product)
{
    // Approach A: pass primitive
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync($"productdetails?id={product.Id}");

    // Approach B: pass complex object
    var nav = new Dictionary<string, object>
    {
        ["product"] = product
    };
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("productdetails", nav);
}
```

**3. Receive data with `IQueryAttributable`**
```csharp
// ProductDetailsViewModel.cs
public partial class ProductDetailsViewModel : ObservableObject, IQueryAttributable
{
    [ObservableProperty] string productId;
    [ObservableProperty] Product product;

    public void ApplyQueryAttributes(IDictionary<string, object> query)
    {
        // Approach A: primitive arrives as string
        if (query.TryGetValue("id", out var id))
            ProductId = id.ToString();

        // Approach B: complex object (passed via dictionary overload)
        if (query.TryGetValue("product", out var obj) && obj is Product p)
            Product = p;
    }
}
```

**4. Wire the ViewModel to the page**
```csharp
// ProductDetailsPage.xaml.cs
public ProductDetailsPage(ProductDetailsViewModel vm)
{
    InitializeComponent();
    BindingContext = vm;
}
```

**Key differences:**

| | String param | Object param |
|---|---|---|
| **Navigate** | `GoToAsync($"...?id={id}")` | `GoToAsync("...", dictionary)` |
| **Arrives as** | `string` in the dictionary | Original `Product` reference |
| **Survives deep-link / URI?** | ✅ Yes | ❌ No (in-process only) |

Use **string IDs** for bookmarkable/deep-linkable routes; use **object passing** when you already have the data loaded and want to avoid a re-fetch.
